In pigs, as well as in humans, evidences suggest that a certain fraction of starch can escape digestion in the upper gastrointestinal tract (GIT), therefore passing into the colon where can be substrate for fermentation ( Williams et al., 2001 ). This fraction, defined as resistant starch (RS), has received great attention in nutritional science, both in humans ( Sajilata et al., 2006; Higgins and Brown, 2013; Birt et al., 2013 ) and in pigs ( Yin et al., 2004; Rideout et al., 2008; Bach Knudsen et al., 2012 ). Nutritionally RS, along with non-starch polysaccharides and non-digestible oligosaccharides, is regarded as non-digestible carbohydrate (NDC, Table 1
). It occurs, basically, in almost all starchy ingredients entering pig diets, but not in a fixed quantity. For instance, raw cereal and legume grains are important natural sources of RS and in vitro analysis indicated that they contain from 50 up to 500
g/kg dry matter (DM) of RS ( Giuberti et al., 2012a; Torres et al., 2013 ).
